    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern civilization is not necessarily the \"end goal\" of human social evolution, but rather one possible branch that has become dominant in the last few millennia. Social evolution is a continuous process where different societies adapt to their environments and needs, and we can see many other forms of organization surviving alongside modern states. The key difference is that modern systems are built on large-scale cooperation and abstract institutions, which allow them to scale far beyond the size of traditional kinship groups. Ultimately, what defines progress is not the complexity of a system, but how well it coordinates human action and sustains its members.",
      "source": "target",
