    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Historians have indeed used the European nation-state and industrial revolution as the primary benchmark for \"civilization,\" which has historically marginalized non-Western societies that developed along different trajectories. This Eurocentric view often treats those alternative paths as less \"advanced\" or even as deviations from the true evolutionary line. However, modern anthropology increasingly recognizes that all complex societies—whether in the Americas, Africa, or Asia—have their own unique forms of social evolution that deserve equal consideration rather than being dismissed as mere precursors.",
